# RapidStack Static Web Project Setup

## Step 1: Open terminal and install RapidStack CLI
```bash
npm install -g @codehance/rapid-stack@latest
```
Verify installation:
```bash
rapid -v
```

## Step 2: Open terminal and navigate to your project folder
```bash
cd Desktop
```

## Step 3: Create project
Run the command below to create your project:
```bash
rapid init
```
When prompted, enter your project name, then:
```bash
cd project-name
```

## Step 4: Open in Cursor
```bash
cursor .
```

## Step 5: Verify Configurations

1. Check local config (.rapidrc):
   - This is the only file in cursor
   - Verify content is correct

2. Check global config:
   ```bash
   cursor ~/.rapid_stack/config.yml
   ```

## Step 6: Required Accounts
Make sure you have created these accounts:
- [ ] GitHub: https://github.com/
- [ ] Cloudflare: https://cloudflare.com/
- [ ] Namecheap: https://namecheap.com/
- [ ] Supabase: https://supabase.com/

## Step 7: Get API Keys and Credentials

1. **Cloudflare Credentials**
   - Log in to Cloudflare dashboard
   - Go to "My Profile" > "API Tokens"
   - Click "Create Token"
   - Select "Create Custom Token"
   - Name it "Your Project Name"
   - Click "Create Token"
   - Add these permissions:
     - Account > Workers Pipelines (Edit)
     - Account > Queues (Edit)
     - Account > Vectorize (Edit)
     - Account > Email Routing Addresses (Edit)
     - Account > Email Routing Addresses (Read)
     - Account > Cloudflare Pages (Edit)
     - Account > Workers R2 Storage (Edit)
     - Account > Workers Tail (Read)
     - Account > Logs (Read)
     - Account > Workers KV Storage (Edit)
     - Account > Workers Scripts (Edit)
     - Account > Workers Scripts (Read)
     - Account > Account Settings (Read)
     - User > Memberships (Read)
     - User > User Details (Read)
     - Zone > Email Routing Rules (Edit)
     - Zone > Email Routing Rules (Read)
     - Zone > Zone Settings (Edit)
     - Zone > Zone (Edit)
     - Zone > Workers Routes (Edit)
     - Zone > DNS (Edit)
   - Copy the token as your `cloudflare_api_key`
   - For `cloudflare_account_id`:
     - Go to dashboard
     - Look at URL: `https://dash.cloudflare.com/<account_id>/...`
     - Or find it in "Account Home" > "Account ID"

2. **GitHub Credentials**
   - Your `github_username` is your GitHub username
   - For `repo_access_token`:
     - Go to GitHub Settings
     - Click your profile picture in the top right
     - Click "Settings" ( scroll down bottom left )
     - Click "Developer settings" > "Personal access tokens" > "Tokens (classic)"
     - Click "Generate new token"
     - Name it "Your Project Name"
     - Select scopes:
       - repo (all)
       - workflow
       - delete_repo
     - Click "Generate token"
     - Copy the token immediately (you won't see it again)

3. **Supabase Credentials**
   - Log in to Supabase dashboard
   - Select your project / create a new project
   - Go to Project Settings > Data API
   - Copy "Project URL" as your `supabase_url`
   - Go to Project Settings > API Keys
   - Copy "anon public" key as your `supabase_anonkey`

## Step 8: Update Global Config
Upon your global config to add required keys:
```bash
cursor ~/.rapid_stack/config.yml
```
Add these to `~/.rapid_stack/config.yml`:
- [ ] cloudflare_api_key
- [ ] cloudflare_account_id
- [ ] github_username
- [ ] repo_access_token
- [ ] email

## Step 9: Update Local Config
Add these to `.rapidrc`:
- [ ] supabase_url
- [ ] supabase_anonkey

## Step 10: Create Static Site
Run this command in cursor terminal:
```bash
rapid build:static --yes --force
```
- `--force` will overwrite existing files
- `--yes` will skip the prompt to confirm changes

You should now have a static site fully configured with Supabase auth as the backend (BaaS).

## Step 11: Start Development Server
```bash
ng serve
```

